fp||cp|2|cs|3|ht|e|at|^b@2DONT stands for "Disturb Opponents No Trump" and it is based on these 2 ideas:

1. If you have a 5-5 hand (or a good 5-4 hand), you can generally do well to declare, 
even when your opponents open 1NT|
pg| ***** 152 ***** |


at|

2. You can put pressure on the opps by making it harder for them to find their best contract - 
if you pass, they will get it right almost all the time|
pg| ***** 153 ***** |


at|

So Marty came up with DONT
It is essentially a way for you to get into the bidding with either a good 1-suiter or a moderate 2-suiter
Here is the structure:

- First, ^*Ba double^*N of 1NT shows a ^*U1-suited hand^*N (and it should be a pretty good suit)
Example - RHO opens 1NT and you  hold xx, KQJ10xx, Axx, Kx
double 
If everyone passes, lead a heart and hope to beat 1NT by a trick or two
(I will get to what pard should do later .. promise!)
You promise a pretty good suit and some stuff|
pg| ***** 154 ***** |


at|

-If you have a ^*U2-suited hand^*N, e.g. Q10xxx, xx, KQxxx, x 
(notice, this is a very weak hand, but its shape is magnificent)
You bid the ^*BLOWER^*N of your two suits
So a bid of 2@C promises clubs and a higher ranking suit
A bid of 2@D shows diamonds and a major
A bid of 2@H promises both majors|
pg| ***** 155 ***** |


nt||cp|2|at|^b@2


So what does 2@S mean? What is the higher suit? Obviously there isn't one! 
So 2@S means "spades" and spades alone:  
Usually a 6 card suit, but if you are dealt a halfway decent suit and an outside K or so, 
something like AJ10xx, xx, Axx, xxx, you may bid 2@S

Remember - your goal isn't necessarily to go plus .. 
but rather to disturb the free flow of information between the opponents
Notice that this is the set of actions you take when ^*BRHO^*N opens 1NT

- One other call.. some people bid ^*B2NT^*N to show ^*Uthe minors^*N
Then a 2@C bid is clubs and a MAJOR

I prefer that a 2NT bid show 5-6 or so in the minors, 
so that I can bid 2@C on a hand like x, xxx, Q10xxx, KJ10x|
